===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}

{{liushu|p}} – [[scorpion]]. The derivative {{och-l|蠆}} refers to the original word. Later phonetically borrowed to refer to {{och-l|萬|ten thousand}}.

===Etymology===
; “scorpion”
: See {{och-l|蠆}}.
; “religious dance; sorcery”
: Perhaps from {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*s-man||medicine}}. Compare {{cog|bo|སྨན||medicine; she-demons worshipped by common folk}}, {{cog|my|မန်း||utter mystic words to heal or ward off evil}}.
; “[[myriad]]; ten thousand”
: {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} considers the etymology of this sense {{der|zh|sit}} and compares it with {{cog|bo|འབུམ||hundred thousand; complete; entire; multifarious}}. Similar words are found in branches of [[Turkic]], [[Mongolic]], [[Tungusic]], [[Korean]], and [[Tocharian]]; here they are treated as very old loanwords from Chinese, per {{zh-ref|Pulleyblank (''apud'' Clauson, 1972)}}, {{zh-ref|Beckwith (2009)}}, {{zh-ref|Adams (2013)}} and {{zh-ref|Tremblay (2005)}}.

